{Olot lies at the Northeast of Spain near the French border. There are
volcanoes and waterfalls in the neighbourhood. A series of ten closed
tournaments were organised by the Club de Ajedrez Olot.   Arturo and Carmen
Pomar Salamanca ran a post office in a village near Barcelona. It was 100 km
south of Olot. Arturo participated in all events.   Installment one was played
by eight persons in Hotel Montsacopa (named after a volcano) from 5 until 12
xii 1966. The Catalan event was won by Pablo Garcia, who scored 6/7. Further
standings were: Pomar Salamanca 51/2, Ulvestad 41/2, Medina Garcia and Pardo 4,
Pares and Gloria Velat 11/2, Bosch 1. The Catalan initiative drew the
attention of the publisher Jorge Puig Laborda. He became the director.   The
second event happened soon. It was played in the same hotel during March 1967.
O'Kelly de Galway won ahead of Medina Garcia. Other participants were Pomar
Salamanca, Ulvestadt, Perez Perez, Pardo Robles, Pares, Llusa and Bosch.
Unfortunately, I could not find games from the first two events.   The third 
tournament was played in Hotel Montsacopa from 17 until 25 ii 1968.
Participants were Damjanovic, Lehmann, Tatai, Durao, Pomar Salamanca, Medina
Garcia and Fernandez. Local heroes from Olot were Parés, Bru and Bosch. So it
had become an international happening. Sponsorship was made by the tourist
sector. Prizes ranged from 20,000 until 1000 pesetas. The next game might have
been important for the final standings.} 1. d4 Nc6 2. Nf3 d6 3. e4 g6 4. d5 Ne5
5. Nxe5 dxe5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Bxd7+ $5 ({Known is} 7. Qd3) 7... Qxd7 8. c4 {
White has a plus in the Nimzowitsch Defence.} e6 9. O-O Bg7 10. Qb3 b6 11. Rd1
f5 $2 ({Preferable is} 11... exd5 12. cxd5 Nf6) 12. Nc3 $1 Nf6 13. c5 exd5 14.
Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Rxd5 Qe6 16. Qa4+ b5 $5 (16... Ke7 17. Bg5+ Bf6 18. f4 {
wins for White.}) 17. Qxb5+ c6 18. Qb7 O-O 19. Rd6 $6 (19. Rd7 $1 Bf6 20. Bh6 {
decides the game quickly.}) 19... Rad8 20. Bg5 $2 (20. Qxc6 {wins easily.})
20... Rxd6 21. cxd6 Qxd6 22. Be7 Qb8 $1 23. Qxc6 Qxb2 $1 24. Qe6+ $5 Kh8 $2 (
24... Rf7 25. Rd1 Bf8 {defends well.}) 25. Rf1 Rb8 26. exf5 gxf5 27. Bf6 f4 $2
(27... Rf8 28. Bxg7+ Kxg7 29. Qe7+ Rf7 {tries to survive.}) 28. h4 Qd4 29. Rc1
Rf8 30. Rc8 Qb4 31. Bxg7+ Kxg7 32. Rc7+ {Pomar diverted from solid style.} 1-0

